            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1858-10-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1858-10-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="87" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d87">
                <head>No. 60.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#center">
                        <hi rend="italic">Report of Captain G. H</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Richards</hi>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1858-10-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 23, 1858</date>, <hi rend="italic">in papers relating to British Columbia, presented
                                    to both Houses of Parliament</hi>, <hi rend="italic">by command
                                    of Her Majesty</hi>, <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 12, 1859.—<hi rend="italic">Part II, p.</hi> 14.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>“The Haro Strait lies between Vancouver Island and the principal islands
                            composing the archipelago. * * In the Haro Strait, Cordova Bay on the
                            western or Vancouver shore offers good anchorage. On Stewart Island,
                            which helps to form the eastern side of the strait, there are snug and
                            land-locked harbors, easily accessible to steamers; and among the
                            Saturna group—the western *boundary of the strait where it enters the
                            Gulf of Georgia—there is good shelter for a fleet, accessible either to
                            sailing-vessels or steamers.”<seg type="margin">Description of Haro
                                channel by Capt. Richards, British Boundary Commissioner.</seg>
                    <seg type="margin">[77]</seg>
                </p>
            </div>
